        <h2 class=rst>The Order of the Arrow National Site</h2>
        <p>I have been a member of Scouting since 2007 when I joined the Cub Scouts. In 2009, I became a member of the Order of the Arrow (also known as, "OA" for short), Scouting's National Honor Society. One of the most facinating things about the OA is that it operated entirely from the local chapter leve to the nation level by youth members under the age of twenty-one. One of my friends became the coordinator for the National Communications and Technology committee and began a major restructoring of what was then an old, poorly functioning group. At that point, I became a member of the production team writing articles and designing for the Order's newspaper, the "National Bulletin".</p>
        <p>In August 2013, I was asked to become a the lead of the order's web development team. Originally built in 1994, the Order of the Arrow  was in need of a redesign. The organization's centennial aniversary was coming up in 2015 and the branding team was beginning a plan to reshape the face of the Order.</p>
        <p>None of the original code from the site was useable; much of the site was static and none of it had ever seen version control. We ended up starting completely from scratch. <p>
