        <small><h5>Expression Engine + Grunt.js + Bower</h5></small>
        {{#markdown}}
The Order's website is built ontop a licensed build of the [ExpressionEngine content management system][ExpressionEngine]. The site uses around six different HTML tempates written in a mixture of PHP and the EE templating language. [Vagrant][vagrant] powers a local development environment that can be used to test files before pushing them to the production server. Deployment is handled through FTP and the ExpressionEngine cPanel.

Templates are stored via Git version control in a private [Github][Github] repository along with the stylesheets, scripts, and any other source files. Generally binary files (except those required for testing), are not stored in Git. We use [Grunt][Grunt] to build and test all final production files and [Bower][Bower] for package management. Since we use a number of packages that were realeased before Bower, Jon and I had to fork those package's repositories, add the required `bower.json` file, and make a pull-request. When our work was done, we had added four commonly used packages to the Bower registry.

We use jQuery and a number of various plugins on the site: [unslider][unslider], for the homepage slider; [jquery-instagram][jquery-instagram], for the Instagram feeds; and, []() for the... . With the exception of a twelve column responsive grid from [Zurb Foundation][Zurb Foundation], all CSS is hand written in [LESS][LESS], a CSS preprocessor that adds variables, functions and mixins to your stylesheets.

The website fully supports all current versions of Chrome, Firefox, Safari and Opera. In order to support CSS3 and HTML5 in Internet Exploerer 8, we use several libraries, pollyfills, and shims: [modernizr][modernizr], [html5shiv][html5shiv], and others. The aim is to not make the website look the same in IE8, but rather just to provide basic functionality.

