        <small><h5>March 2014 by Patrick Burtchaell</h5></small>
        {{#markdown}}
The redesigned site successfully launched on December 24 and by Christmas the DNS had propagated. It was a pretty awesome Christmas present for the organization. After a presentation of the website at the National Planning Meeting in Dallas, I recived plenty of compliments from everyone. My team and I have spent the last month taking a break from the site.

As of February 2014, the codebase of the website contains a lot of extra bulk that is completely unnecessary. In December, things were taking longer than we expected to work out all the bugs and add in all the last minute feature requests, so things got a bit messy. By June 2014, I hope to have finished a code review and implemented all solutions.

#### Expression Engine
As none of us had used it before, ExpressionEngine was definitely a new territory for myself and my team. We had to learn a new templating language and because of licenses, we had no way to properly test anything locally. This was a huge setback. Had a depolyment system been in place and development server, we would have been much more productive and finished more features. No matter how many times I stressed this to my leadership coordinators who have access to the server, this was ignored and pushed to the backlog. "We will address it in 2014", I was told.

For a period of time in the beginning of development, this was okay. Our templates were mostly PHP so we could test them using a local -AMP stack. However, as we began to add functions from the EE templating language, it was extremely to *copy and paste* the templates to the EE cPanel each time a change was made, save the template, and refresh the page. I think I easily spend 10 percent of my time on this process.

In order to solve the problem of not having a development server, Eric finished up a Vagrant build to emulate a basic copy of EE locally on each developer's machine. This would have solved our issues, had we received the database from our leadership team. Since neither myself nor any one else on my team have access to the production server, there was no way for me to access a copy of the database. I requested the database multiple times from the team leadership, but to my dissapointment, my reqeest was also put on the "we will get to it in 2014" backlog. At the time of writing, I still do not have a copy of the database. Clearly, leadership has become numb to the painful process my team uses to deploy. If you can call copy-and-pasting into a cPanel deplyment.

I must say I very must so dislike EE templates. It is a very awkward configuration. While EE is certianly very powerful and has much potential, it is not necessarily great out of the box. Unlike many modern content management systems, it requires much more configuration and add-ons to achieve your goals. However, for this project, I quickly realized that the coordinators did not understand this. Only two of the add-ons were installed.

Overall, I do not think the three-hundred dollars that ExpressionEngine costs is worthwhile at all. There are many better open-source options out there if you want a CMS more powerful than your typical Wordpress install. [Drupal]() works great and the technologies that power [Ghost]() make it a very sustainable alternative. Besides being more configurable, these alternaives will be more familiar to a developer. EE requires an "ExpressionEgine Developer" to fully use it to its potential. This means that you not only have to spend $300, but also have to do extra training to get used to it.

