Moving the codebase to private Github repositories worked very well. Not only was it a great way to control the source, but project mangement was perfectly solved with the issues tracker and milestones. At the moment we currently also use Trello in tandem with Github. We also plan to convert our [oa-bsa user account](http://github.com/oa-bsa) to an organization. It was slightly ineffective to not have administration access and to be using an account rather than an organization, which would have alloweed for better management. For this reason, we are currently in the process of switching the acount from a user to an organizations.

#### Project Management
The greatest difficulty in building the Order's website is the politics that come along with decisions. Whenever I need to do something envolving the server, I need to email my coordinator who then emails his adviser. Anything envolving money needs to get approved by somone two steps up the leadership chain.

When it comes to code, my team can do whatever they want. I have adapted a "as long as it achieves the end result I desire, you can use whatever means you want to get there" method of tasking for my team. It works very well. I task out an assignment, tell the developer what he has to do, and then let them go. A few days later I'll get a notification that the issue has been solved.

This difficulty prevented my team from making the website as good as it could be. For example, in the beginning of development I asked if we could install an add-on that required the content team to write content in [Markdown]() rather than the horrific WYSIWYG editor built into EE. The EE editor styles its content by using inlinestyles that overrides the site's stylesheet. This caused for inconsistent styles all across the board &mdash;also known as an ugly site. I brought this to my coordinators' attention expecting an understanding response. To my surprise this request was ignored with another paraphrased "we'll get to it later" email. For this reason, many of the pages on the site look horrible thanks to the EE editor.

#### Documentation
I think the initial documentation for the site came much to late in the year. For this reason, the team was off to a slow start. However, the team has done a very good job of documenting the processess we use for development. From installation to configuration, our usage of Vagrant, Grunt, and Bower is very well documented. In the future, I plan to document both a formal code styleguide and site stylegude.
